This was written by a VET of the Korean War on another thread. It had disturbed me to the extent that I thought it important enough to repost in its own thread.<br><br>
VETERANS RECOGNITION<br>
Thu May 1 22:04:45 US/Eastern 1997 <br><br>
I have heard so much about the Vietnam situation, and how<br>
forgotten they were, and it grinds me when I think of how quickly everyone has put the Korean &quot;peace initiative&quot; behind them. Yes, I was in the Korean &quot;thing&quot;, but they didn't build any wall to those who died there, and you sure as hell haven't heard much from those Vets.<br><br>
So what's the point??? Perhaps a reflecting wall that mirrors the Vietnam wall - I think it's wrong to treat WWII vets like saviors, forget the Korean vets, and now fawn all attentions on Vietnam vets. A vet is a vet, and all either did lay down their lives for their country or at least were there and were willing to. Vets should be treated like Vets! <br><br>
-- kennard_kaplan@compuserve.com (Ken Kaplan) <br><br>
I sent Ken an e-mail and it is as follows:<br><br>
Ken,<br><br>
I apologize for the fact that there may be vets of WWII and especially Vietnam who would object to your views as you posted on the POV site. Like I said, my only uncle was a vet of that war. I know that it had a great impact on him and, ultimately, lead to his commiting suicide. I agree that Korea was and is the Forgotten War. But, I do not know what I can do about it. The only thing I can say is that, I served two years in 'Nam as a combat medic in a infantry unit, and for all the shit I went through, and surviving, I don't think I would have survived much of what had occurred in Korea. Though my uncle never spoke of his experiences, just as my dad never spoke of his, I went out of my way after he died to learn what I could of the Korean War and what he went through.<br><br>
Not all of us has forgotten your contributions (and sacrifices) or the contributions of your fellow vets, to this country. Not all of us has forgotten what those contributions had cost you.<br><br>
Doc Del<br><br>
To my fellow vets: You may take issue with the fact that his anger and frustrations may be misplaced, but before doing so, just remember that it was only five years or so after the war in 'Nam had ended before we got vet centers and the like, but it was twenty six years or so before these vets could take advantage of these same benefits. If any of you want dispute the fact that I know what I am talking about, e-mail me and I will gladly give you my uncles name and grave marker number at Punchbowl National Cemetary.<br><br>
These vets lived through the same crap that you and I had when we came home for a lot longer period of time. And they did it ALONE. Do you remember what it was like?<br><br>
Let's rock n' roll, guys
